  <sec>
   <title>
    Introduction
   </title>
   <p>
    Hop (
    <em>
     H
    </em>
    sp70/Hsp90-
    <em>
     o
    </em>
    rganizing
    <em>
     p
    </em>
    rotein) has been described as a cofactor in a multichaperone complex with the cytosolic chaperones heat shock protein (Hsp) 90 and Hsp70.
    <a>
     <sup>
      1
     </sup>
    </a>
    Albeit not acting as a chaperone itself, Hop is required for the efficient activation of steroid hormone receptors (SHRs) by the Hsp70–Hsp90 system.
    <a>
     <sup>
      2
     </sup>
    </a>
    Hop has been shown in multiple experiments to bind to an initial complex of SHR with Hsp70 and the chaperone Hsp40.
    <sup>
     <a>
      3
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      4
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      5
     </a>
    </sup>
    The main purpose of the interaction between Hsp70, Hop, and Hsp90 is to promote substrate transfer from Hsp70 to Hsp90, which occurs in the ternary complex under ATP hydrolysis by Hsp70.
    <a>
     <sup>
      6
     </sup>
    </a>
    Subsequent activation of the SHR requires ATP hydrolysis by Hsp90 and the exchange of the protein complex Hsp40·Hsp70·Hop for other cofactors, namely, p23 and FKBP51/52.
    <sup>
     <a>
      7
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      8
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      9
     </a>
    </sup>
   </p>
   <p>
    The binding of Hop to the C-terminal amino acids IEEVD of Hsp70 is mediated by its tetratricopeptide repeat (TPR) 1 domain.
    <sup>
     <a>
      10
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      11
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      12
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      13
     </a>
    </sup>
    The TPR2A domain of Hop provides the main interaction site for the C-terminal MEEVD motif of Hsp90, which allows the formation of the ternary Hsp90·Hop·Hsp70 complex in yeast and human systems.
    <sup>
     <a>
      12
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      14
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      15
     </a>
    </sup>
    In addition to TPR1 and TPR2A, all characterized Hop proteins contain a putative third TPR domain without an assigned function (TPR2B) and two linker domains: one between TPR1 and TPR2A, called DP1, and one at the C-terminus of the protein, called DP2. The DP1 domain is absent in
    <em>
     Drosophila
    </em>
    .
    <a>
     <sup>
      16
     </sup>
    </a>
    It is intriguing that the putative homologue of Hop in the genome of
    <em>
     Caenorhabditis elegans
    </em>
    does not contain a coding sequence for the Hsp70-binding TPR1/DP1 domain despite a strong homology throughout the TPR2A, TPR2B, and DP2 domains. We observed that a Hop protein lacking the TPR1 domain can only be detected in the genomes of
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    and its close relatives
    <em>
     Caenorhabditis briggsae
    </em>
    and
    <em>
     Caenorhabditis remanei
    </em>
    , besides a few other mostly unconfirmed homologues of lower eukaryotes (
    <em>
     Cryptosporidium hominis
    </em>
    and
    <em>
     Schistosoma japonicum
    </em>
    ).
   </p>
   <p>
    Apart from being analyzed in mammalian cell culture, Hop has been analyzed in yeast, where a homologue of Hop, termed Sti1, is found.
    <a>
     <sup>
      17
     </sup>
    </a>
    Sti1 strongly inhibits the ATPase activity of yeast Hsp90
    <a>
     <sup>
      18
     </sup>
    </a>
    in stark contrast to the mammalian homologue, which does not inhibit the hydrolysis of human Hsp90.
    <a>
     <sup>
      19
     </sup>
    </a>
    For the Hsp90·Sti1 complex, the mechanism of ATPase inhibition has been investigated. Interaction with Sti1 prevents a crucial conformational change in Hsp90, which has been shown to be essential for the ATP-hydrolyzing reaction,
    <a>
     <sup>
      20
     </sup>
    </a>
    albeit mechanistic details regarding the binding sites involved in ATPase inhibition have not been performed. Functional analysis in yeast shows that although the protein seems to be not essential in
    <em>
     sti1
    </em>
    knockout strains, synthetic phenotypes that result in growth defects and lethality exist.
    <sup>
     <a>
      21
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      22
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      23
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      24
     </a>
    </sup>
    Genes that show synthetic lethality with
    <em>
     sti1
    </em>
    knockout strains include the Hsp40 homologue
    <em>
     ydj1
    </em>
    ;
    <sup>
     <a>
      23
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      24
     </a>
    </sup>
    the Hsp90 cochaperones
    <em>
     sba1
    </em>
    ,
    <sup>
     <a>
      21
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      24
     </a>
    </sup>
    <em>
     cpr7
    </em>
    ,
    <a>
     <sup>
      24
     </sup>
    </a>
    and
    <em>
     cdc37
    </em>
    ;
    <a>
     <sup>
      22
     </sup>
    </a>
    and the genes for KIN28, CDC7, CEP3, and EPS1, some of which were identified in large-scale genomewide screens.
    <sup>
     <a>
      25
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      26
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      27
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      28
     </a>
    </sup>
    Moreover, deletion of
    <em>
     sti1
    </em>
    in yeast reduces the activity of two heterologous Hsp90 targets, namely glucocorticoid receptor and v-Src.
    <sup>
     <a>
      17
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      21
     </a>
    </sup>
    For several of these synergistic effects, the reasons have not been determined, leaving the cellular function of Sti1, in part, unclear.
   </p>
   <p>
    We aimed to address the function of the Hop homologue from
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    and further attempted to understand to what extent the current biochemical knowledge about Hop/Sti1 applies to this exotic variant. Our results describe the first organismal function of Hop in a metazoan and address the mechanism of interaction between the
    <em>
     Caenorhabditis elegans
    </em>
    Hop homologue R09E12.3 (CeHop), Hsp70, and Hsp90.
   </p>
  </sec>
  <sec>
   <title>
    Results
   </title>
   <title>
    Hop proteins show specific domain loss in nematodes
   </title>
   <p>
    A homologue of Hop in the nematode
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    has been identified by genome sequencing and automated annotation of open reading frames (ORFs).
    <a>
     <sup>
      29
     </sup>
    </a>
    The closest homologue of human Hop in
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    is encoded by the gene
    <em>
     R09E12.3
    </em>
    . The predicted ORF lacks sequences for the TPR1 domain and encodes a 340-amino-acid protein that resembles a truncated version of the 543-amino-acid human protein (
    <a>
     Fig. 1
    </a>
    a). Nevertheless, alignment of different Hop proteins detects a strong sequence homology in the sequences of the TPR2A, TPR2B ,and DP2 domains (
    <a>
     Fig. 1
    </a>
    b), hinting strongly at a conserved function of the remaining domains.
   </p>
  </sec>
