   <p>
    We were interested to see how common this domain organization is among Hop-like proteins. In the public genome databases, only a few other Hop proteins that share the domain organization of the gene
    <em>
     R09E12.3
    </em>
    can be found. Based on today's sequence availability, only about 2% of the sequenced Hop genes encode a truncated Hop protein (data not shown). Most of these are encoded by nematode genomes, namely
    <em>
     C. briggsae
    </em>
    and other close relatives of
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    .
   </p>
   <p>
    It has been observed in eukaryotic proteins that loss of domains is sometimes accompanied by the emergence of another protein that, in turn, could be complemented by complex formation. We therefore searched the
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    genome for proteins that encode TPR motifs similar to the lost TPR1 domain, using TPR1 from yeast and human Hop proteins as bait in the searches (
    <a>
     Table 1
    </a>
    ). The strongest homology was found for TPR2B of
    <em>
     R09E12.3
    </em>
    itself, while other proteins identified were the homologues of the well-described Hsp90 cochaperones CNS1, SGT1, and CHIP. Therefore, we conclude that the loss of the TPR1 domain in the gene
    <em>
     R09E12.3
    </em>
    is not compensated for by another protein, while the remaining domains of CeHop form a protein with a close homology to other eukaryotic Hop proteins.
   </p>
