   <p>
    In order to confirm constitutive expression and to investigate which tissues actually express the Hop homologue, we fused the 1.5-kb promoter region of the gene to YFP and generated stable
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    lines by microinjection. We could detect expression from this construct in all major tissues at normal growth temperature (
    <a>
     Fig. 2
    </a>
    b). A particularly strong expression was observed in the intestine, pharynx, spermathecae, and body-wall muscle cells.
   </p>
   <title>
    The truncated CeHop protein is required for the development of fertility
   </title>
   <p>
    Next, we were interested to find an organismal function for the TPR1-depleted CeHop. Thus, we performed RNA interference (RNAi) experiments to characterize knockdown phenotypes. Upon knockdown of CeHop/R09E12.3 in wildtype nematodes (
    <em>
     N2
    </em>
    Bristol), we were unable to observe phenotypes consistent with results obtained in large genomic screens
    <a>
