    </em>
    appear to develop only small, oddly shaped spermathecae and a few sperms. Based on these RNAi experiments, we conclude that the TPR1-depleted Hop protein exerts cellular functions that can be uncovered as synthetic phenotype in
    <em>
     hsf-1(sy441)
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     R09E12.3(RNAi)
    </em>
    and might particularly be required during the development of fertility.
   </p>
   <title>
    CeHop binds to Hsp90 and inhibits its ATPase activity
   </title>
   <p>
    Having shown that this exotic Hop homologue is widely expressed and participates in organismal processes, we aimed to understand its biochemical properties, as the deletion of TPR1 could affect all proposed biochemical functions of Hop. We therefore investigated whether the ability of this protein to interact with Hsp90 is compromised. First, we tested its interaction with Hsp90 by coimmunoprecipitation after addition of His
    <sub>
     6
    </sub>
    -CeHop to whole animal extracts. His
    <sub>
     6
    </sub>
    -CeHop was pulled down by Ni-NTA matrices, and attached proteins were analyzed by Western blot analysis. Indeed, we observed an interaction of Hsp90 when His
    <sub>
     6
    </sub>
    -CeHop was added, while control experiments in the absence of His
    <sub>
     6
    </sub>
    -CeHop did not result in the pulldown of Hsp90 (
    <a>
     Fig. 3
    </a>
    a).
   </p>
