   <p>
    In order to quantify the binding behavior of CeHop to Hsp90, we purified
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    Hsp90 from recombinant
    <em>
     Escherichia coli
    </em>
    cultures and determined the binding affinities using a surface plasmon resonance (SPR)-based binding assay. The calculated dissociation constant was 204 ± 22 nM for direct titrations (
    <a>
     Fig. 3
    </a>
    b), and a similar value was obtained in competition experiments (
    <a>
     Fig. 3
    </a>
    c). In agreement with data for other eukaryotic systems, the binding of CeHop to Hsp90 was critically dependent on the MEEVD motif at the C-terminus of Hsp90, as a mutant lacking the MEEVD motif did not show competition with chip-coupled Hsp90 (
    <a>
     Fig. 3
    </a>
    c).
   </p>
   <p>
    We next tested whether CeHop binding has an effect on the ATP turnover rate of Hsp90.
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    Hsp90 was found to hydrolyze ATP with a turnover rate of 0.8 min
    <sup>
     − 1
    </sup>
    , slightly higher than that of yeast Hsp90 (
    <em>
     k
    </em>
    <sub>
     cat
    </sub>
    = 0.4 min
    <sup>
     − 1
    </sup>
    ) and far higher than that of human Hsp90 (
    <em>
     k
    </em>
    <sub>
     cat
    </sub>
    = 0.03 min
    <sup>
     − 1
    </sup>
    ). Addition of increasing concentrations of CeHop to Hsp90 has a strong inhibitory effect (
    <a>
     Fig. 3
    </a>
    d) on the Hsp90 turnover rate. Again, no inhibition of ATPase activity was observed in a mutant lacking the MEEVD motif at the C-terminal end of Hsp90.
   </p>
   <p>
    These data imply that the mechanism of the
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    Hop homologue—at least regarding Hsp90—closely resembles the mechanism of the yeast homologue Sti1, which also acts as a potent inhibitor of the Hsp90 ATPase, while the human Hsp90 protein, with its significantly lower ATP turnover and noninhibitory Hop interaction, remains different.
   </p>
   <title>
    CeHop binds to Hsc70 in the absence of TPR1
   </title>
   <p>
    Next, we were interested on whether the loss of TPR1 in CeHop compromises the binding of heat shock cognate (Hsc) 70. No distinction regarding the binding of the heat-inducible Hsp70 or the constitutively expressed Hsc70, which share a sequence identity in excess of 90%, has so far been made. Therefore, the constitutive Hsp70 protein Hsc70/
    <em>
     F26D10.3
    </em>
    /HSP-1 was purified from recombinant expression cultures. Hsc70 then was coupled to the chip surface for SPR studies to investigate CeHop binding. Indeed, upon addition of CeHop to the sensor surface, we observed an interaction between CeHop and chip-bound Hsc70 in direct binding assays (
    <a>
     Fig. 4
    </a>
    a). The interaction was rather weak (
    <em>
     K
    </em>
    <sub>
     d
    </sub>
    = 2.7 ± 0.3 μM) compared to the affinity for Hsp90 but similar to published Hsp70·Hop complexes from yeast and human systems.
    <a>
     <sup>
      31
     </sup>
    </a>
    As the interaction of Hsc70 with CeHop does not involve the characterized Hsc70-binding site, we were interested on whether the IEEVD motif at the C-terminal end of Hsc70 is still responsible for this effect. Therefore, we generated an SPR chip by coupling the Hsc70 mutant Hsc70-ΔIEEVD to its surface and investigated the binding of CeHop to the sensor surface. Binding of CeHop was abolished, showing the specificity of the interaction and the requirement of the IEEVD motif for the interaction between CeHop and Hsc70 even in the absence of TPR1 (
    <a>
     Fig. 4
    </a>
    a).
   </p>
