   <p>
    Having seen binding between Hsc70 and CeHop, we were interested to see whether CeHop influences the turnover of Hsc70. Purified Hsc70 was found to hydrolyze ATP with a turnover rate of 0.3 min
    <sup>
     − 1
    </sup>
    . No influence on the ATP turnover of Hsc70 was detected, even at CeHop concentrations far above the determined binding constant (
    <a>
     Fig. 4
    </a>
    b).
   </p>
   <p>
    Therefore, we conclude that the TPR1-depleted Hop homologue from
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    surprisingly is still capable of binding Hsc70, potentially via the other TPR domains, but fails to stimulate the ATPase activity of Hsc70. This implies that the interaction between these two proteins might functionally not be comparable to the observed interaction of yeast Ssa1 and Sti1/Hop.
    <a>
     <sup>
      31
     </sup>
    </a>
   </p>
   <title>
    Binding of Hsp90 to CeHop competes with Hsc70 binding
   </title>
   <p>
    The apparent complexity of the binary binding of CeHop to either Hsc70 or Hsp90 raised the important question of whether a ternary complex, as proposed in yeast or mammals previously, can be formed even in the absence of the Hsp70-binding site TPR1. We therefore tested whether Hsp90 can compete for the binding of Hop to Hsc70 using the SPR interaction assay. Hsc70 was coupled to the sensor surface and binding of CeHop was observed upon injection, as reported previously (see
    <a>
     Fig. 4
    </a>
    a). Maintaining constant concentrations of CeHop during the injections, we added increasing concentrations of Hsp90 to the injection solution in order to preform Hsp90-CeHop complexes. Addition of higher concentrations of Hsp90 fully abolished the binding of CeHop to Hsc70 (
    <a>
     Fig. 5
    </a>
    ). An increase in the concentration of CeHop required proportionally increased amounts of Hsp90 to suppress binding (
    <a>
     Fig. 5
    </a>
    ). Again, deletion of the MEEVD motif from Hsp90 precludes its binding to CeHop and prevents the inhibitory effect of Hsp90 on the formation of Hsp90-CeHop complexes (
    <a>
     Fig. 5
    </a>
    ). These results imply that Hsp90 binding to CeHop efficiently prevents binding of CeHop to Hsc70 and, therefore, Hsc70 and Hsp90 apparently compete for binding to the
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    Hop homologue.
   </p>
