   <title>
    Regulation of Hsp90 requires both TPR domains of CeHop
   </title>
   <p>
    The inability to simultaneously bind Hsc70 and Hsp90 to the two TPR domains of CeHop raises the question of potentially overlapping binding sites. We therefore aimed to analyze which domains of CeHop participate in the binding of Hsp90 and Hsc70. We individually purified TPR2A (N131-CeHop) and the C-terminal domain, including TPR2B (129C-CeHop). Both domains exhibited a stability similar to that of full-length CeHop, as judged from thermal transitions employing CD spectroscopy and urea transitions (data not shown).
   </p>
   <p>
    We first aimed to characterize the binding of the Hop fragments to Hsc70. Here, N131-CeHop did bind Hsc70 with a weak binding affinity, implying that this domain serves as an interaction site with Hsc70. 129C-CeHop as well showed a weak but unquantifiable interaction with Hsc70 (
    <a>
     Table 3
    </a>
    ). Neither fragment was able to influence ATP turnover by Hsc70 (
    <a>
     Table 3
    </a>
    ).
   </p>
