   <p>
    We next tested the binding behavior of the individual Hop domains towards Hsp90. N131-CeHop bound to Hsp90 with a—compared to CeHop—10-fold reduced affinity of 1.98 ± 0.3 μM (
    <a>
     Table 3
    </a>
    ). The isolated TPR2B domain 129C-CeHop did not bind Hsp90 (
    <a>
     Table 3
    </a>
    ). Interestingly, N131-CeHop also was unable to suppress the ATPase activity of Hsp90 at concentrations significantly higher than the binding constant of the TPR2A–Hsp90 complex (
    <a>
     Table 3
    </a>
    ).
   </p>
   <p>
    These findings indicate that, while both TPR domains have some affinity for Hsc70, the full-length CeHop is required for the high affinity binding of Hsp90 for CeHop. The 10-fold reduction in the affinity of N131-CeHop for Hsp90 and the lack of any regulation of the Hsp90 ATPase in complex with isolated TPR2A imply that the second TPR domain significantly contributes to the binding reaction and the functional interaction between CeHop and Hsp90.
   </p>
   <p>
    The combination of these results suggests that—contrary to findings in the yeast and mammalian multichaperone systems—the two chaperones bind competitively to CeHop and that weak binding of Hsc70 is disrupted in the presence of Hsp90.
   </p>
   <title>
    Hsp90 knockdown leads to Hop-like defects during gonad development
   </title>
   <p>
    Hop is not known to perform cellular functions independent of Hsp90 and Hsc70. Having established that the
    <em>
     C. elegans
    </em>
    homologue of Hop is able to bind to Hsc70 or Hsp90, we were interested to see whether RNAi knockdown can show involvement of either of the two chaperones in cellular effects seen during the knockdown of CeHop/R09E12.3. Therefore, RNAi experiments were performed using constructs targeted at Hsp90/
    <em>
     daf-21
    </em>
    and Hsc70/
    <em>
     hsp-1
    </em>
    in
    <em>
     N2
    </em>
    and
    <em>
     hsf-1(sy441)
    </em>
    . Contrarily to
    <em>
     R09E12.3(RNAi)
    </em>
    ,
    <em>
     daf-21(RNAi)
    </em>
    and
    <em>
     hsp-1(RNAi)
    </em>
    are known to be arrested during larval development,
    <sup>
     <a>
      30
     </a>
     ,
     <a>
      32
     </a>
     and
     <a>
      33
     </a>
    </sup>
    resulting in early larval arrest in the case of
    <em>
     N2
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     hsp-1(RNAi)
    </em>
    ,
    <em>
     hsf-1(sy441)
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     hsp-1(RNAi)
    </em>
    , and
    <em>
     hsf-1(sy441)
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     daf-21(RNAi)
    </em>
    (
    <a>
     Table 4
    </a>
    ).
    <em>
     N2
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     daf-21(RNAi)
    </em>
    developed a protruding vulva phenotype and late larval arrest. In order to prevent early larval arrest phenotypes and to allow detection of phenotypes during gonad development, we started the knockdown at developmental stages of L1, L2, and L3 larvae. We did not observe features of the phenotypes described for
    <em>
     hsf-1(sy441)
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     R09E12.3(RNAi)
    </em>
    during knockdown of Hsc70, as either early larval arrest (starting with L1 or L2) or wildtype (starting with L3) phenotypes were observed. In
    <em>
     N2
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     daf-21(RNAi)
    </em>
    , we did observe a phenotype with limited similarity to
    <em>
     hsf-1(sy441)
    </em>
    /
    <em>
     R09E12.3(RNAi)
    </em>
    (
    <a>
     Fig. 6
    </a>
    a,
    <a>
     Table 4
    </a>
    ). While the nematodes displayed late larval arrest and developed a protruding vulva, in particular, the shortened arms on either the proximal gonad or the distal gonad and the development of endomitotic oocytes were observable.
   </p>
